title: Architectural Assistant
description: Design achievements: - Modelling the firm’s refurbishment proposal for Elephant and Castle Shopping Centre in London. I was responsible for all stages of the modelling process including development of a 3d model in SketchUp and the production of a video for a latter presentation to the clients. - Design of a canopy for the new bus station at the Friars Walk shopping centre development in Newport, Wales. The original concept consisted of a simple building with little visual relationship to the remainder of the project. My proposal was for the structure of the canopy to mirror the façade layout of the adjoining shopping centre to generate a game of shadows, integrating the two buildings (which are owned by different parties) within the wider project. - Volumetric (i.e. massing) proposals for the development of new housing blocks on land to the east of Wembley Stadium in London. Nine proposals were generated and three were selected to be developed and prepared for 3d printing.

title: In-house Architect and designer
description: Key responsibilities: • In-house architect responsible for all aspects of design and budgeting for the company’s roll-out programme. I have designed shops and kiosks for locations including Selfridges (Oxford St), Bluewater, The Oracle (Reading) and The Friary (Guildford). • Collaborated with designers from Ben and Jerry’s and Odeon to develop a Snog kiosk for cinemas. The first kiosk is under construction and will be trialled at the Odeon cinema in Milton Keynes. • Directly involved in the budgeting and value management process for new locations, liaising with manufacturers and the project manager to produce a design that matches financial requirements. • Responsible for securing necessary licenses from London Councils for existing and new shops, • Design and development of new architectural and marketing elements to enhance customer experience in the new kiosks and existing shops. Also in charge of collaboration with the internal marketing department and third-party graphic designers for the creation and installation of all artwork material across the retail estate. • Marketing support role involving the production of in-house graphic design pieces (promotional material, menu amendments and others) Key achievements: • Production of kiosk designs within budget and time constraints, allowing the company to establish a roll-out model for future shops while optimising capex and enhancing payback periods. • Development of new architectonic/marketing pieces that have helped to transfer the high-street shop experience into the shopping centre kiosk. • Selfridge’s kiosk was designed in a single day to take advantage of an extremely time-limited commercial opportunity. I was in charge of the design of the new shop for this location, including collaboration with marketing, graphic designers and builders.
